description:
In this video, I walk through my complete workflow for tackling large coding projects using Claude Code's plan mode. I demonstrate how to start with a rough dictated prompt, use plan mode to explore the codebase and generate clarifying questions, and break complex work into multi-phase plans that can span multiple context windows. I show my custom rules configuration that keeps plans concise and adds unresolved questions, how to monitor context usage throughout implementation, and my strategy of storing plans as GitHub issues to preserve them across context resets. This approach combines upfront planning with aggressive auto-accept during implementation phases, allowing AI to handle substantial features while maintaining control and code quality. I share practical tips including my favorite concision rule, the benefits of multi-phase planning, and how to effectively manage context windows for large projects.

Become an AI Hero with my AI SDK v5 Crash Course:

https://www.aihero.dev/workshops/ai-sdk-v5-crash-course

Follow Matt on Twitter

https://twitter.com/mattpocockuk

https://aihero.dev/discord

comments.text:
Planning and Setup
[00:44] Activate "plan mode" when starting a large task  To ensure Claude Code thinks through the steps first.

[00:50] Always create a plan first for a big piece of work  To force the AI to explore the codebase and identify unclear specifications.

[02:40] Use the memory command  To access and edit your user and project memory rules.

[02:53] Instruct the AI in your rules to be "extremely concise"  To get plans that are easier and faster to read.

[03:05] Add a rule to always ask for "unresolved questions" at the end of a plan  To ensure all ambiguities are surfaced before coding begins.

[03:34] Dictate your answers to the AI's clarifying questions  To provide input quickly.

Plan Execution and Iteration
[04:13] Break large tasks into a multi-phase plan  To prevent overrunning the LLM's context window.

[04:19] Tell the AI to "make the plan multi-phase"  To instruct it to break down the implementation steps.

[04:53] Swap to "auto-accept edit" mode after the plan is complete  To begin executing the planned steps.

[05:00] Tell the AI to "execute phase one"  To start the implementation of the first part of your plan.

[05:40] Exit Claude Code (e.g., Ctrl+C) to run local commands  To use other tools like VS Code or Git.

[05:49] Run Claude continue in your terminal  To resume your session exactly where you left off.

[06:24] Stage or commit your changes between each phase  To make it clear what code was added in each step.

[07:15] Tell the AI to "pull the files into your context" if you make an external change  To inform the AI of any manual edits or formatter runs.

Context and Workflow Management
[04:37] Check your context window usage periodically  To avoid running out of space during a large feature implementation.

[07:54] Store multi-phase plans in an external asset, like a GitHub issue  To preserve the plan even if you need to reset the context window.

[07:58] Instruct the AI to "make a GitHub issue containing the current plan"  To automatically create an external record of the plan and its progress.

[08:13] Clear the context window after saving the plan externally  To free up tokens for the next phase of a large task.

[08:31] Tell the AI to "get the GitHub issue [number] and enact phase [number]"  To load the plan from the issue and continue working in a new context.

Recommended Configurations
[09:52] Add a rule to your memory file to be extremely concise  To improve the readability and speed of AI interactions.

[09:58] Add a rule to your memory file to produce unresolved questions  To ensure all ambiguities are handled during the planning stage.

[09:58] Add a rule to your memory file to use the GitHub CLI  To enable the AI to create issues for context sharing.

comments.text:
A great video. I'm assuming you wouldn't just vibe your way through the plan if its real work. 

I just have a huge problem trying to get a multi phase plan in place. It becomes a huge mental chore to do it. Because every slight change, I have to force clear my own context, and re-read the whole thing, to be sure that the revised plan is correct. And to be honest there is usually some bit that I'm fuzzy on which "i will figure out when i get to it".

And so it just doesn't seem to work. I make a plan for something that I never follow to the end, or do in a different order. Then I refine the plan as I'm chatting to the ai and implementing it. What am I going to do then? Go back and update the plan for features I have already now made? No. So the plan is never very authoritative.

I've used tasks a bit (I'm using AugmentCode at the moment), which will give me notes for the upcoming steps that i might implement, and lets me do it in any order. 

But my best experience with ai, for satisfaction and correct code being generated that trust, is to just go along and build it as I go, one bit at a time, with an immediate check and refinement cycle; not making big plan documents.

comments.text:
You can add token usage to your status line. 
In ~/.claude/settings.json add `"statusLine": { "type": "command", "command": "bash ~/.claude/statusline/main.sh" }`. Then, in `~/.claude/statusline/main.sh` add:

```bash
#!/bin/bash
input=$(cat)
transcript_path=$(echo "$input" | jq -r '.transcript_path // ""')

if [ -f "$transcript_path" ]; then
  token_estimate=$(($(wc -c < "$transcript_path") / 4))
  context_percent=$(echo "scale=1; $token_estimate * 100 / 200000" | bc -l)
  echo "$token_estimate/200k tokens ($context_percent%)"
fi
```

In my opinion, Claude code is not the agent for engineers or engineering. Well, this is more of a critique of Anthropic's models. They seemed to have done some data augmentation or synthetic data generation that taught the model bizzare patterns. Occasionally their models do unthinkable things.

For example, leaving a comment that acknowledges a highly critical bug exists, but claiming its "intentional" then proceeding to justify why its good that this bug exists. I cannot fathom a human ever doing this, this behavior must of been learned from augmented or synthetic data. It doesn't make any sense. I almost think the bug existing without the comment would be preferable, as it would indicate more logically consistent output.

Then you also have Claude's classic "You're completely right, I deleted your database" bit, which is funny, but it is something that Claude actually does. 

Using Claude for engineering is like trying calculate half of a number N by flipping a coin N times and counting the number of heads. Except, the law of large numbers doesn't apply and the result gets further as the code in Claude context window increases.

comments.text:
I feel like people don't quite understand the concept of 'leveraging' AI for coding. You're not relying on it entirelyyou still need to debug & tweak but if you understand what AI is useful for then it can dramatically boost your productivity.

For me it's really all about understanding how to have an active, ongoing live-debugging session with itasking it the right questions, utilizing screenshots, reverting back, there's quite a few techniques, but I actually think it makes coding a lot more entertaining, and it also helps explain to me what my knowledge gaps are without having to scour the depths of the internet for hyper specific technical information.

Personally, I use two AI programs at once: Claude browser for basic coding & version control (with manual editing in Visual Studio which I then upload back into Claude), and then Copilot quite literally as if it were a copilot sort of helping me out on the side with any questions I might have while staying separate from Claude's work area.

Great video Matt! In my day to day I work across a lot of technologies and some pretty old and unfamiliar codebases. AI tools like Claude have reached a point where for implementation workflows, codebase exploration, and debugging they dont slow me down and I dont see them as a hindrance. There is a lot of negativity out there that isn't well explained and some of these comments are honestly cringe.

Healthy skepticism is good but outright dismissiveness isn't. If you tried using GitHub Copilot several months ago it was awful at exploring or even referencing your codebase when answering questions and was basically a waste of time, but it has gotten better. AI is just another tool, not a substitute for learning. I don't use it to learn mobile, embedded, or game development, but for accelerating workflows where you already have strong expertise it is legit. A video like this where a developer review the plan and look at the changes are wonderful because these are real workflows. Thanks again. comments.text:
I think, it's always about how you use it. Do you think it takes all your work? No. The AI is stupid af. So, the first steps are always: Do you know what you want, have you a plan in mind how to approch and then let the AI do the execution, and fix if there was a misunderstanding. For me it's great to let the AI do verbose tasks like creating models, database scheames, basic UI form and so many boring repeated tasks. And if you really have something where some brain cells are needed, you can do it your self and use AI to assist in maybe finding the issue, let it write tests for you and all that... It's co-working not "do everything for me and I should take my brain and put it into a form filled with water".
And one thing, what's shown in this video: For complicated tasks, let the AI do first a task-list, clairfiy questions, and let it do the task. Works great if such a list is there where the AI then can look back and know what to do even if the context window gets bigger, and starting a new instance is also no problem, since the task-list is it's anchor to continue the work.

comments.text:
@mattpocockukFirst of all, I'm not unsubscribing because this channel still provides good videos, especially the effect-ts one, which I found out thanks to you.

With that said, I'm sorry but this saying that AI is an amazing tool for devs is simply not true. First, the thoery. As I said in my comment above, these LLMs DO NOT THINK! They do not reaaon, they do not "know" things, they have no awareness, no concept of time, no concept of logic, no concept of understanding. They output the next best word based on a huge series of markov-like chains. I understand why people in finance or management think that LLMs are smart because they have no idea what's AI, but I don't understand why developers do not see this. 

We learned all our life that software is complicated, so complicated in fact that we developed abstractions over abstractions to try and make software simpler to create, for better or for worse. To expect these AI models to actually do all this complicated work by using probability to determine the next keyword is hilarious and the only reason we got here is because people are betting literally trillions of dollars at this point that AI will somehow be useful.

Sorry for the long rant, and my comment is not aimed to your channel per se, but to the type of content. Unfortunately, the algo pushes this content and anyone who doesn't understand how AI works will keep thinking it's magic and create hype around it, and creators who don't follow the hype are punished. 

Anyways, it's your channel, your choice, but I really really like your typescript videos. I learned a lot from them!
